# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alivenci
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Acaçá is the only ritual food required in Candomblé; it is offered to all the orixás in the Candomblé pantheon.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Acaçá made of white corn is offered to Oxala; that made of yellow corn is offered to Oxossi.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Acaçá is made of white or red corn soaked in water for a day, which is then passed through a mill to make a paste or dough.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] The paste or dough is cooked in a pan and stirred continuously to reach a correct consistency.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] While warm, small portions of the dough are wrapped in a clean, folded clean banana leaf and passed over a fire.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Finely ground white cornmeal can be substituted for soaked corn.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] The acaçá is cut into pieces of equal size.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] They are arranged on a platter to be placed on or near a *pegi*, or Candomblé altar.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] They also decorate other ritual foods in Candomblé, notably vatapá.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto (Portuguese: *acaçá of black beans*) is a variation of the acaçá made from black beans, i.e., the black turtle bean (*Phaseolus vulgaris*).
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Black beans are substituted for soaked corn, similarly made into a paste, wrapped in banana leaves, and steamed in a pan.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Acaçá de feijão-preto is specifically offered to the god Ogum.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] The variation of acaçá is associated with Casa Fanti Ashanti, a Candomblé temple of the Jeje-Nagô tradition in the neighborhood of Cruzeiro do Anil, São Luís, in the state of Maranhão.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Acaçá de leite (transl. acaçá of milk) is a fermented drink used in Candomblé rituals.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] It is made from a corn mush to which milk and other seasonings are added.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] Acaçá de leite is found in Candomblé temples in Bahia and the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] A variation, acaçá de leite de coco, is made from coconut milk.
[src:alivenci/acaçá] This variation is found in the state of Rio de Janeiro.
[src:alivenci/aligot] Traditionally made with fresh tomme de Laguiole (tomme fraîche), or tomme d'Auvergne cheese, aligot is highly appreciated in the local gastronomy with thick Toulouse sausages or roast beef.
[src:alivenci/aligot] Other cheeses are sometimes used in place of fresh tomme, which is hard to get by as it should ideally be used in the days following its making, or else it will be too strong in taste.
[src:alivenci/aligot] The choice of cheese is important, and strongly affects the result.
[src:alivenci/aligot] The cheese must be mild, with a lactic tang, but not too much salt, and melt easily.
[src:alivenci/aligot] Floury potatoes are preferable, rather than waxy.
[src:alivenci/aligot] Aligot is made from mashed potatoes blended with butter, cream, and melted cheese, often but not always with crushed garlic.
[src:alivenci/aligot] The dish is ready when it develops a smooth, elastic texture.
[src:alivenci/aligot] While recipes vary, the Larousse Gastronomique gives the ingredients as 1 kg potatoes; 500 g tomme fraîche, Laguiole, or Cantal cheese; 2 garlic cloves; 30 g butter; salt and pepper.
[src:alivenci/aligot] This dish was prepared for pilgrims on the way to Santiago de Compostela who stopped for a night in that region.
[src:alivenci/aligot] According to legend, aligot was originally prepared with bread, and potatoes were substituted after their introduction to France.
[src:alivenci/aligot] Today, it is enjoyed for village gatherings and celebrations as a main dish.
[src:alivenci/aligot] In the region of Aubrac, and more generally in the south of Auvergne, Aligot is still cooked by hand in homes and street markets.
[src:alivenci/aligot] During the summer, it is the main (and often only) dish served in traditional farm buildings known as "burons", where cows used to be milked, that are converted into seasonal restaurants.
[src:alivenci/aligot] The name *aligot* may have been derived from the Occitan *alicouot*, from the Latin *aliquid*, or from the Old French *harigoter*.
[src:alivenci/alivenci] A form of cheesecake was very popular in Ancient Greece.
[src:alivenci/alivenci] The secret of its manufacture was passed during the Roman invasions.
[src:alivenci/alivenci] At that time, the Latin name used for this type of cake was placenta that was transmitted in Romanian culture.
[src:alivenci/alivenci] For Saint Peter, the Moldovan prepare alivenci.
[src:alivenci/amandine-dessert] These cakes are among the most traditional "sweetshop" cakes in Romania.
[src:alivenci/amandine-dessert] The original recipe has layers of chocolate sponge cake soaked in rum flavored caramel syrup.
[src:alivenci/amandine-dessert] The cream filling is a combination of chocolate buttercream mixed with fondant.
[src:alivenci/amandine-dessert] The assembled layers are glazed with a combination of fondant with chocolate and rum or rum essence, poured over the cake while still slightly liquid.
[src:alivenci/amandine-dessert] These cakes also have a traditional decoration on top with a little bit of the cream and a diamond-shaped piece of thin chocolate.
[src:alivenci/amylomaize] Amylomaize starch is principally used in making biodegradable plastics (or bioplastics).
[src:alivenci/amylomaize] It is also used in edible and digestible coatings.
[src:alivenci/amylomaize] The food consumed on Apollo space flights from 1969 to 1972 were coated with an amylomaize film to prevent crumbs from floating around the space capsule.
[src:alivenci/amylomaize] Bear had discovered and reported that waxy corn (100% amylopectin starch) also occurred as a mutation.
[src:alivenci/amylomaize] Once discovered and reported, waxy mutations were found in the order of once every 30,000 observations.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Three centuries after the decline of Mycenaean Greece during the Bronze Age collapse, Greek urban poleis began to form in the 8th century BC, ushering in the Archaic period and the colonization of the Mediterranean Basin.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period is considered to have ended in 30 BC, when the last Hellenistic kingdom, Ptolemaic Egypt, was annexed by the Roman Republic.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Classical Greek culture, especially Greek philosophy, had a powerful influence on ancient Rome, which carried a version of it throughout the Mediterranean and much of Europe.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] For this reason, Classical Greece is generally considered the cradle of Western civilization, the seminal culture from which the modern West derives many of its founding archetypes and ideas in politics, philosophy, science, and art.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in the Mediterranean region is commonly considered to have begun in the 8th century BC (around the time of the earliest recorded poetry of Homer) and ended in the 6th century AD.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Classical antiquity in Greece was preceded by the Greek Dark Ages (c.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] 800 BC), archaeologically characterised by the protogeometric and geometric styles of designs on pottery.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Following the Dark Ages was the Archaic period, beginning around the 8th century BC, which saw early developments in Greek culture and society leading to the Classical period from the Persian invasion of Greece in 480 BC until the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Classical period is characterized by a "classical" style, i.e. one which was considered exemplary by later observers, most famously in the Parthenon of Athens.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Politically, the Classical period was dominated by Athens and the Delian League during the 5th century, but displaced by Spartan hegemony during the early 4th century BC, before power shifted to Thebes and the Boeotian League and finally to the League of Corinth led by Macedon.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] This period was shaped by the Greco-Persian Wars, the Peloponnesian War, and the Rise of Macedon.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Following the Classical period was the Hellenistic period (323–146 BC), during which Greek culture and power expanded into the Near East from the death of Alexander until the Roman conquest.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Roman Greece is usually counted from the Roman victory over the Corinthians at the Battle of Corinth in 146 BC to the establishment of Byzantium by Constantine as the capital of the Roman Empire in 330 AD.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Finally, Late Antiquity refers to the period of Christianization during the later 4th to early 6th centuries AD, consummated by the closure of the Academy of Athens by Justinian I in 529.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The historical period of ancient Greece is unique in world history as the first period attested directly in comprehensive, narrative historiography, while earlier ancient history or protohistory is known from much more fragmentary documents such as annals, king lists, and pragmatic epigraphy.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Herodotus is widely known as the "father of history": his *Histories* are eponymous of the entire field.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Written between the 450s and 420s BC, Herodotus' work reaches about a century into the past, discussing 6th-century BC historical figures such as Darius I of Persia, Cambyses II and Psamtik III, and alluding to some 8th-century BC persons such as Candaules.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The accuracy of Herodotus' works is debated.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Herodotus was succeeded by authors such as Thucydides, Xenophon, Demosthenes, Plato and Aristotle.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Most were either Athenian or pro-Athenian, which is why far more is known about the history and politics of Athens than of many other cities.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Their scope is further limited by a focus on political, military and diplomatic history, ignoring economic and social history.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The archaic period, lasting approximately from 800 to 500 BC, saw the culmination of political and social developments which had begun in the Greek Dark Age, with the *polis* (city-state) becoming the most important unit of political organisation in Greece.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The absence of powerful states in Greece after the collapse of Mycenaean power, and the geography of Greece, where many settlements were separated from their neighbours by mountainous terrain, encouraged the development of small independent city-states.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Several Greek states saw tyrants rise to power in this period, most famously at Corinth from 657 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The period also saw the founding of Greek colonies around the Mediterranean, with Euboean settlements at Al-Mina in the east as early as 800 BC, and Ischia in the west by 775.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Increasing contact with non-Greek peoples in this period, especially in the Near East, inspired developments in art and architecture, the adoption of coinage, and the development of the Greek alphabet.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Athens developed its democratic system over the course of the archaic period.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Already in the 7th century, the right of all citizen men to attend the assembly appears to have been established.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] After a failed coup led by Cylon of Athens around 636 BC, Draco was appointed to establish a code of laws in 621.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] This failed to reduce the political tension between the poor and the elites, and in 594 Solon was given the authority to enact another set of reforms, which attempted to balance the power of the rich and the poor.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the middle of the 6th century, Pisistratus established himself as a tyrant, and after his death in 527 his son Hippias inherited his position; by the end of the 6th century he had been overthrown, and Cleisthenes carried out further democratising reforms.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In Sparta, a political system with two kings, a council of elders, and five ephors developed over the course of the 8th and 7th centuries.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] According to Spartan tradition, this constitution was established by the legendary lawgiver Lycurgus.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Over the course of the First Messenian War and Second Messenian War, Sparta subjugated the neighbouring region of Messenia, enserfing the population.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the 6th century, Greek city-states began to develop formal relationships with one another, where previously individual rulers had relied on personal relationships with the elites of other cities.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Towards the end of the Archaic period, Sparta began to build a series of alliances, the Peloponnesian League, with cities including Corinth, Elis, and Megara, isolating Messenia and reinforcing Sparta's position against Argos, the other major power in the Peloponnese.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Other alliances in the 6th century included those between Elis and Heraea in the Peloponnese; and between the Greek colony Sybaris in southern Italy, its allies, and the Serdaioi.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In 499 BC, the Ionian city-states under Persian rule rebelled against their Persian-supported tyrant rulers.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Supported by troops sent from Athens and Eretria, they advanced as far as Sardis and burnt the city before being driven back by a Persian counterattack.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The revolt continued until 494, when the rebelling Ionians were defeated.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Darius did not forget that Athens had assisted the Ionian revolt, and in 490 he assembled an armada to retaliate.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Though heavily outnumbered, the Athenians—supported by their Plataean allies—defeated the Persian hordes at the Battle of Marathon, and the Persian fleet turned tail.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Ten years later, a second invasion was launched by Darius' son Xerxes.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The city-states of northern and central Greece submitted to the Persian forces without resistance, but a coalition of 31 Greek city-states, including Athens and Sparta, determined to resist the Persian invaders.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] At the same time, Greek Sicily was invaded by a Carthaginian force.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Persians were decisively defeated at sea by a primarily Athenian naval force at the Battle of Salamis, and on land in 479 BC at the Battle of Plataea.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The alliance against Persia continued, initially led by the Spartan Pausanias but from 477 by Athens, and by 460 Persia had been driven out of the Aegean.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] During this long campaign, the Delian League gradually transformed from a defensive alliance of Greek states into an Athenian empire, as Athens' growing naval power intimidated the other league states.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Athens ended its campaigns against Persia in 450, after a disastrous defeat in Egypt in 454, and the death of Cimon in action against the Persians on Cyprus in 450.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] As the Athenian fight against the Persian empire waned, conflict grew between Athens and Sparta.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Suspicious of the increasing Athenian power funded by the Delian League, Sparta offered aid to reluctant members of the League to rebel against Athenian domination.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] These tensions were exacerbated in 462 BC when Athens sent a force to aid Sparta in overcoming a helot revolt, but this aid was rejected by the Spartans.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the 450s, Athens took control of Boeotia, and won victories over Aegina and Corinth.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, Athens failed to win a decisive victory, and in 447 lost Boeotia again.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Athens and Sparta signed the Thirty Years' Peace in the winter of 446/445, ending the conflict.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Despite the treaty, Athenian relations with Sparta declined again in the 430s, and in 431 BC the Peloponnesian War began.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The first phase of the war saw a series of fruitless annual invasions of Attica by Sparta, while Athens successfully fought the Corinthian empire in northwest Greece and defended its own empire, despite a plague which killed the leading Athenian statesman Pericles.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The war turned after Athenian victories led by Cleon at Pylos and Sphakteria, and Sparta sued for peace, but the Athenians rejected the proposal.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Athenian failure to regain control of Boeotia at Delium and Brasidas' successes in northern Greece in 424 improved Sparta's position after Sphakteria.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] After the deaths of Cleon and Brasidas, the strongest proponents of war on each side, a peace treaty was negotiated in 421 by the Athenian general Nicias.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In 418 BC allied forces of Athens and Argos were defeated by Sparta at Mantinea.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In 415 Athens launched an ambitious naval expedition to dominate Sicily; the expedition ended in disaster at the harbor of Syracuse, with almost the entire army killed, and the ships destroyed.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Soon after the Athenian defeat in Syracuse, Athens' Ionian allies began to rebel against the Delian league, while Persia began to once again involve itself in Greek affairs on the Spartan side.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Initially the Athenian position continued relatively strong, with important victories at Cyzicus in 410 and Arginusae in 406.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, in 405 the Spartan Lysander defeated Athens in the Battle of Aegospotami, and began to blockade Athens' harbour; driven by hunger, Athens sued for peace, agreeing to surrender their fleet and join the Spartan-led Peloponnesian League.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Following the Athenian surrender, Sparta installed an oligarchic regime, the Thirty Tyrants, in Athens, one of a number of Spartan-backed oligarchies which rose to power after the Peloponnesian war.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Spartan predominance did not last: after only a year, the Thirty had been overthrown.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The first half of the 4th century saw the major Greek states attempt to dominate the mainland; none were successful, and their resulting weakness led to a power vacuum which was eventually filled by Macedon under Philip II and then Alexander the Great.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the immediate aftermath of the Peloponnesian war, Sparta attempted to extend their own power, leading Argos, Athens, Corinth, and Thebes to join against them.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Aiming to prevent any single Greek state gaining the dominance that would allow it to challenge Persia, the Persian king initially joined the alliance against Sparta, before imposing the Peace of Antalcidas ("King's Peace") which restored Persia's control over the Anatolian Greeks.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] By 371 BC, Thebes was in the ascendancy, defeating Sparta at the Battle of Leuctra, killing the Spartan king Cleombrotus I, and invading Laconia.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Further Theban successes against Sparta in 369 led to Messenia gaining independence; Sparta never recovered from the loss of Messenia's fertile land and the helot workforce it provided.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The rising power of Thebes led Sparta and Athens to join forces; in 362 they were defeated by Thebes at the Battle of Mantinea.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the aftermath of Mantinea, none of the major Greek states were able to dominate.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Though Thebes had won the battle, their general Epaminondas was killed, and they spent the following decades embroiled in wars with their neighbours; Athens, meanwhile, saw its second naval alliance, formed in 377, collapse in the mid-350s.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The power vacuum in Greece after the Battle of Mantinea was filled by Macedon, under Philip II, starting from the battle of Crocus field.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In 338 BC, he defeated a Greek alliance at the Battle of Chaeronea, and subsequently formed the League of Corinth.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Philip planned to lead the League to invade Persia, but was murdered in 336 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] His son Alexander the Great was left to fulfill his father's ambitions.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] After campaigns against Macedon's western and northern enemies, and those Greek states that had broken from the League of Corinth following the death of Philip, Alexander began his campaign against Persia in 334 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] He conquered Persia, defeating Darius III at the Battle of Issus in 333 BC, and after the Battle of Gaugamela in 331 BC proclaimed himself king of Asia.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] From 329 BC he led expeditions to Bactria and then India; further plans to invade Arabia and North Africa were halted by his death in 323 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The period from the death of Alexander the Great in 323 BC until the death of Cleopatra, the last Macedonian ruler of Egypt, is known as the Hellenistic period.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the early part of this period, a new form of kingship developed based on Macedonian and Near Eastern traditions.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The first Hellenistic kings were previously Alexander's generals, and took power in the period following his death, though they were not part of existing royal lineages and lacked historic claims to the territories they controlled.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the early part of the Hellenistic period, the exact borders of the Hellenistic kingdoms were not settled.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Antigonus attempted to expand his territory by attacking the other successor kingdoms until they joined against him, and he was killed at the Battle of Ipsus in 301 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] His son Demetrius spent many years in Seleucid captivity, and his son, Antigonus II, only reclaimed the Macedonian throne around 276.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Meanwhile, the Seleucid kingdom gave up territory in the east to the Indian king Chandragupta Maurya in exchange for war elephants, and later lost large parts of Persia to the Parthian Empire.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] By the mid-3rd century, the kingdoms of Alexander's successors was mostly stable, though there continued to be disputes over border areas.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The great capitals of Hellenistic culture were Alexandria in the Ptolemaic Kingdom and Antioch in the Seleucid Empire.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The conquests of Alexander had numerous consequences for the Greek city-states.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] It greatly widened the horizons of the Greeks and led to a steady emigration of the young and ambitious to the new Greek empires in the east.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Many Greeks migrated to Alexandria, Antioch and the many other new Hellenistic cities founded in Alexander's wake, as far away as present-day Afghanistan and Pakistan, where the Greco-Bactrian Kingdom and the Indo-Greek Kingdom survived until the end of the 1st century BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Some city-states within Greece formed themselves into two major leagues; the Achaean League (including Corinth and Argos) and the Aetolian League.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] For much of the period until the Roman conquest, these leagues were at war, often participating in the conflicts between the Diadochi's successor states to Alexander's empire.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Antigonid Kingdom became involved in a war with the Roman Republic in the late 3rd century.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Although the First Macedonian War was inconclusive, the Romans, in typical fashion, continued to fight Macedon until it was completely absorbed into the Roman Republic (by 149 BC).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the east, the unwieldy Seleucid Empire gradually disintegrated, although a rump survived until 64 BC, whilst the Ptolemaic Kingdom continued in Egypt until 30 BC when it too was conquered by the Romans.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Aetolian league grew wary of Roman involvement in Greece, and sided with the Seleucids in the Roman–Seleucid War; when the Romans were victorious, the league was effectively absorbed into the Republic.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Although the Achaean league outlasted both the Aetolian league and Macedon, it was also soon defeated and absorbed by the Romans in 146 BC, bringing Greek independence to an end.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Greek peninsula came under Roman rule during the 146 BC conquest of Greece after the Battle of Corinth.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Macedonia became a Roman province while southern Greece came under the surveillance of Macedonia's prefect; however, some Greek *poleis* managed to maintain a partial independence and avoid taxation.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Aegean Islands were added to this territory in 133 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Athens and other Greek cities revolted in 88 BC, and the peninsula was crushed by the Roman general Sulla.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Roman civil wars devastated the land even further, until Augustus organized the peninsula as the province of Achaea in 27 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Greece was a key eastern province of the Roman Empire, as the Roman culture had long been in fact Greco-Roman.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Greek language served as a *lingua franca* in the East and in Italy, and many Greek intellectuals such as Galen would perform most of their work in Rome.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The territory of Greece is mountainous, and as a result, ancient Greece consisted of many smaller regions, each with its own dialect, cultural peculiarities, and identity.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Regionalism and regional conflicts were prominent features of ancient Greece.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Cities tended to be located in valleys between mountains, or on coastal plains, and dominated a certain area around them.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the south lay the Peloponnese, consisting of the regions of Laconia (southeast), Messenia (southwest), Elis (west), Achaia (north), Korinthia (northeast), Argolis (east), and Arcadia (center).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] These names survive to the present day as regional units of modern Greece, though with somewhat different boundaries.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Mainland Greece to the north, nowadays known as Central Greece, consisted of Aetolia and Acarnania in the west, Locris, Doris, and Phocis in the center, while in the east lay Boeotia, Attica, and Megaris.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Northeast lay Thessaly, while Epirus lay to the northwest.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Epirus stretched from the Ambracian Gulf in the south to the Ceraunian Mountains and the Aoos river in the north, and consisted of Chaonia (north), Molossia (center), and Thesprotia (south).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the northeast corner was Macedonia, originally consisting Lower Macedonia and its regions, such as Emathia (Macedonia), Pieria, and Bottiaea, and later Almopia, Amphaxitis.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The original capital of Macedon was Aigai and then moved to Pella in the 4th century BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] To the north of Macedonia lay various non-Greek peoples such as the Paeonians due north, the Thracians to the northeast, and the Illyrians, with whom the Macedonians were frequently in conflict, to the northwest.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Chalcidice was settled early on by southern Greek colonists and was considered part of the Greek world, while from the late 2nd millennium BC substantial Greek settlement also occurred on the eastern shores of the Aegean, in Anatolia.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] This was not simply for trade, but also to found settlements.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] These Greek colonies were not, as Roman colonies were, dependent on their mother-city, but were independent city-states in their own right.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Greeks settled outside of Greece in two distinct ways.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The first was in permanent settlements founded by Greeks, which formed as independent poleis.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The second form was in what historians refer to as *emporia*; trading posts which were occupied by both Greeks and non-Greeks and which were primarily concerned with the manufacture and sale of goods.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Examples of this latter type of settlement are found at Al Mina in the east and Pithekoussai in the west.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] From around 750 to 500 BC, Greeks settled colonies in all directions.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] To the east, the Aegean coast of Asia Minor was colonized first, followed by Cyprus and the coasts of Thrace, the Sea of Marmara and the south coast of the Black Sea.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Eventually, Greek colonization reached as far northeast as present-day Ukraine and Russia (Taganrog).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] To the west the coasts of Illyria, Southern Italy (called "Magna Graecia") were settled, followed by Southern France, Corsica, and even eastern Spain.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Greek colonies were also founded in Egypt and Libya.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Modern Syracuse, Naples, Marseille and Istanbul had their beginnings as the Greek colonies Syracusae (Συράκουσαι), Neapolis (Νεάπολις), Massalia (Μασσαλία) and Byzantion (Βυζάντιον).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] These colonies played an important role in the spread of Greek influence throughout Europe and also aided in the establishment of long-distance trading networks between the Greek city-states, boosting the economy of ancient Greece.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Ancient Greece consisted of several hundred relatively independent city-states (*poleis*).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] This was a situation unlike that in most other contemporary societies, which were either tribal or kingdoms ruling over relatively large territories.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Undoubtedly, the geography of Greece—divided and sub-divided by hills, mountains, and rivers—contributed to the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] On the one hand, the ancient Greeks had no doubt that they were "one people"; they had the same religion, same basic culture, and same language.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Furthermore, the Greeks were very aware of their tribal origins; Herodotus was able to extensively categorise the city-states by tribe.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Yet, although these higher-level relationships existed, they seem to have rarely had a major role in Greek politics.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The independence of the *poleis* was fiercely defended; unification was something rarely contemplated by the ancient Greeks.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Even when, during the second Persian invasion of Greece, a group of city-states allied themselves to defend Greece, the vast majority of *poleis* remained neutral, and after the Persian defeat, the allies quickly returned to infighting.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Thus, the major peculiarities of the ancient Greek political system were its fragmented nature (and that this does not particularly seem to have tribal origin), and the particular focus on urban centers within otherwise tiny states.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The peculiarities of the Greek system are further evidenced by the colonies that they set up throughout the Mediterranean, which, though they might count a certain Greek *polis* as their 'mother' (and remain sympathetic to her), were completely independent of the founding city.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Inevitably smaller *poleis* might be dominated by larger neighbors, but conquest or direct rule by another city-state appears to have been quite rare.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Instead the *poleis* grouped themselves into leagues, membership of which was in a constant state of flux.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Later in the Classical period, the leagues would become fewer and larger, be dominated by one city (particularly Athens, Sparta and Thebes); and often *poleis* would be compelled to join under threat of war (or as part of a peace treaty).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Even after Philip II of Macedon conquered the heartlands of ancient Greece, he did not attempt to annex the territory or unify it into a new province, but compelled most of the *poleis* to join his own Corinthian League.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Initially many Greek city-states seem to have been petty kingdoms; there was often a city official carrying some residual, ceremonial functions of the king (*basileus*), e.g., the *archon basileus* in Athens.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, by the Archaic period and the first historical consciousness, most had already become aristocratic oligarchies.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] It is unclear exactly how this change occurred.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] For instance, in Athens, the kingship had been reduced to a hereditary, lifelong chief magistracy (*archon*) by c.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] 1050 BC; by 753 BC this had become a decennial, elected archonship, and finally an annually elected archonship by 683 BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Through each stage, more power would have been transferred to the aristocracy as a whole, and away from a single individual.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Inevitably, the domination of politics and concomitant aggregation of wealth by small groups of families was apt to cause social unrest in many *poleis*.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In many cities a tyrant (not in the modern sense of repressive autocracies), would at some point seize control and govern according to their own will; often a populist agenda would help sustain them in power.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In a system wracked with class conflict, government by a 'strongman' was often the best solution.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Athens fell under a tyranny in the second half of the 6th century BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] When this tyranny was ended, the Athenians founded the world's first democracy as a radical solution to prevent the aristocracy regaining power.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] A citizens' assembly (the *Ecclesia*), for the discussion of city policy, had existed since the reforms of Draco in 621 BC; all citizens were permitted to attend after the reforms of Solon (early 6th century), but the poorest citizens could not address the assembly or run for office.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] With the establishment of the democracy, the assembly became the *de jure* mechanism of government; all citizens had equal privileges in the assembly.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, non-citizens, such as metics (foreigners living in Athens) or slaves, had no political rights at all.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] After the rise of democracy in Athens, other city-states founded democracies.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, many retained more traditional forms of government.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] As so often in other matters, Sparta was a notable exception to the rest of Greece, ruled through the whole period by not one, but two hereditary monarchs.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Kings of Sparta belonged to the Agiads and the Eurypontids, descendants respectively of Eurysthenes and Procles.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Both dynasties' founders were believed to be twin sons of Aristodemus, a Heraclid ruler.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, the powers of these kings were held in check by both a council of elders (the *Gerousia*) and magistrates specifically appointed to watch over the kings (the *Ephors*).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Only free, land-owning, native-born men could be citizens entitled to the full protection of the law in a city-state.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In most city-states, unlike the situation in Rome, social prominence did not allow special rights.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Sometimes families controlled public religious functions, but this ordinarily did not give any extra power in the government.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In Athens, the population was divided into four social classes based on wealth.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] People could change classes if they made more money.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In Sparta, all male citizens were called *homoioi*, meaning "peers".
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, Spartan kings, who served as the city-state's dual military and religious leaders, came from two families.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Women in Ancient Greece appear to have primarily performed domestic tasks, managed households, and borne and reared children.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Slaves had the right to have a family and own property, subject to their master's goodwill and permission, but they had no political rights.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] By 600 BC, chattel slavery had spread in Greece.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] By the 5th century BC, slaves made up one-third of the total population in some city-states.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Between 40 and 80% of the population of Classical Athens were slaves.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Slaves outside of Sparta almost never revolted because they were made up of too many nationalities and were too scattered to organize.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, unlike later Western culture, the ancient Greeks did not think in terms of race.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Most families owned slaves as household servants and laborers, and even poor families might have owned a few slaves.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Owners were not allowed to beat or kill their slaves.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Owners often promised to free slaves in the future to encourage slaves to work hard.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Unlike in Rome, freedmen did not become citizens.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Instead, they were mixed into the population of *metics*, which included people from foreign countries or other city-states who were officially allowed to live in the state.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] These public slaves had a larger measure of independence than slaves owned by families, living on their own and performing specialized tasks.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In Athens, public slaves were trained to look out for counterfeit coinage, while temple slaves acted as servants of the temple's deity and Scythian slaves were employed in Athens as a police force corralling citizens to political functions.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Sparta had a special type of slaves called *helots*.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Helots were Messenians enslaved en masse during the Messenian Wars by the state and assigned to families where they were forced to stay.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Helots raised food and did household chores so that women could concentrate on raising strong children while men could devote their time to training as hoplites.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Their masters treated them harshly, and helots revolted against their masters several times.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In 370/369 BC, as a result of Epaminondas' liberation of Messenia from Spartan rule, the helot system there came to an end and the helots won their freedom.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] However, it persisted in Laconia until the 2nd century BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] For most of Greek history, education was private, except in Sparta.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] During the Hellenistic period, some city-states established public schools.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Only wealthy families could afford a teacher.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Boys learned how to read, write and quote literature.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] They also learned to sing and play one musical instrument and were trained as athletes for military service.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] They studied not for a job but to become an effective citizen.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Girls also learned to read, write and do simple arithmetic so they could manage the household.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] They almost never received education after childhood.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Boys went to school at the age of seven, or went to the barracks, if they lived in Sparta.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The three types of teachings were: grammatistes for arithmetic, kitharistes for music and dancing, and Paedotribae for sports.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Boys from wealthy families attending the private school lessons were taken care of by a *paidagogos*, a household slave selected for this task who accompanied the boy during the day.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Classes were held in teachers' private houses and included reading, writing, mathematics, singing, and playing the lyre and flute.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] When the boy became 12 years old the schooling started to include sports such as wrestling, running, and throwing discus and javelin.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In Athens, some older youths attended academy for the finer disciplines such as culture, sciences, music, and the arts.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The schooling ended at age 18, followed by military training in the army usually for one or two years.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Some of Athens' greatest such schools included the Lyceum (the so-called Peripatetic school founded by Aristotle of Stageira) and the Platonic Academy (founded by Plato of Athens).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The education system of the wealthy ancient Greeks is also called Paideia.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] At its economic height in the 5th and 4th centuries BC, the free citizenry of Classical Greece represented perhaps the most prosperous society in the ancient world, some economic historians considering Greece one of the most advanced pre-industrial economies.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In terms of wheat, wages reached an estimated 7–12 kg (15–26 lb) daily for an unskilled worker in urban Athens, 2–3 times the 3.75 kg (8.3 lb) of an unskilled rural labourer in Roman Egypt, though Greek farm incomes too were on average lower than those available to urban workers.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] At least in the Archaic period, the fragmentary nature of ancient Greece, with many competing city-states, increased the frequency of conflict but conversely limited the scale of warfare.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Unable to maintain professional armies, the city-states relied on their own citizens to fight.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] This inevitably reduced the potential duration of campaigns, as citizens would need to return to their own professions (especially in the case of, for example, farmers).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Campaigns would therefore often be restricted to summer.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] When battles occurred, they were usually set piece and intended to be decisive.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Casualties were slight compared to later battles, rarely amounting to more than five percent of the losing side, but the slain often included the most prominent citizens and generals who led from the front.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The scale and scope of warfare in ancient Greece changed dramatically as a result of the Greco-Persian Wars.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] To fight the enormous armies of the Achaemenid Empire was effectively beyond the capabilities of a single city-state.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The eventual triumph of the Greeks was achieved by alliances of city-states (the exact composition changing over time), allowing the pooling of resources and division of labor.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Although alliances between city-states occurred before this time, nothing on this scale had been seen before.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The rise of Athens and Sparta as pre-eminent powers during this conflict led directly to the Peloponnesian War, which saw further development of the nature of warfare, strategy and tactics.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Fought between leagues of cities dominated by Athens and Sparta, the increased manpower and financial resources increased the scale and allowed the diversification of warfare.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Set-piece battles during the Peloponnesian war proved indecisive and instead there was increased reliance on attritionary strategies, naval battles and blockades and sieges.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] These changes greatly increased the number of casualties and the disruption of Greek society.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Athens owned one of the largest war fleets in ancient Greece.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] It had over 200 triremes each powered by 170 oarsmen who were seated in 3 rows on each side of the ship.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The city could afford such a large fleet—it had over 34,000 oarsmen—because it owned a lot of silver mines that were worked by slaves.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] According to Josiah Ober, Greek city-states faced approximately a one-in-three chance of destruction during the archaic and classical period.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek philosophy focused on the role of reason and inquiry.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In many ways, it had an important influence on modern philosophy, as well as modern science.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Clear unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers, to medieval Muslim philosophers and Islamic scientists, to the European Renaissance and Enlightenment, to the secular sciences of the modern day.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Neither reason nor inquiry began with the ancient Greeks.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Defining the difference between the Greek quest for knowledge and the quests of the elder civilizations, such as the ancient Egyptians and Babylonians, has long been a topic of study by theorists of civilization.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The first known philosophers of Greece were the pre-Socratics, who attempted to provide naturalistic, non-mythical descriptions of the world.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] They were followed by Socrates, one of the first philosophers based in Athens during its golden age whose ideas, despite being known by second-hand accounts instead of writings of his own, laid the basis of Western philosophy.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Socrates' disciple Plato, who wrote *The Republic* and established a radical difference between ideas and the concrete world, and Plato's disciple Aristotle, who wrote extensively about nature and ethics, are also immensely influential in Western philosophy to this day.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The later Hellenistic philosophy, also originating in Greece, is defined by names such as Antisthenes (cynicism), Zeno of Citium (stoicism) and Plotinus (Neoplatonism).
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek literature was poetry and was composed for performance rather than private consumption.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The earliest Greek poet known is Homer, although he was certainly part of an existing tradition of oral poetry.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Homer's poetry, though it was developed around the same time that the Greeks developed writing, would have been composed orally; the first poet to certainly compose their work in writing was Archilochus, a lyric poet from the mid-7th century BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Tragedy developed around the end of the archaic period, taking elements from across the pre-existing genres of late archaic poetry.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Like poetry, Greek prose had its origins in the archaic period, and the earliest writers of Greek philosophy, history, and medical literature all date to the 6th century BC.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Prose first emerged as the writing style adopted by the presocratic philosophers Anaximander and Anaximenes—though Thales of Miletus, considered the first Greek philosopher, apparently wrote nothing.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Prose as a genre reached maturity in the classical era, and the major Greek prose genres—philosophy, history, rhetoric, and dialogue—developed in this period.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period saw the literary centre of the Greek world move from Athens, where it had been in the classical period, to Alexandria.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] At the same time, other Hellenistic kings such as the Antigonids and the Attalids were patrons of scholarship and literature, turning Pella and Pergamon respectively into cultural centres.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] It was thanks to this cultural patronage by Hellenistic kings, and especially the Museum at Alexandria, that so much ancient Greek literature has survived.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Library of Alexandria, part of the Museum, had the previously unenvisaged aim of collecting together copies of all known authors in Greek.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Almost all of the surviving non-technical Hellenistic literature is poetry, and Hellenistic poetry tended to be highly intellectual, blending different genres and traditions, and avoiding linear narratives.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Hellenistic period also saw a shift in the ways literature was consumed—while in the archaic and classical periods literature had typically been experienced in public performance, in the Hellenistic period it was more commonly read privately.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] At the same time, Hellenistic poets began to write for private, rather than public, consumption.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] With Octavian's victory at Actium in 31 BC, Rome began to become a major centre of Greek literature, as important Greek authors such as Strabo and Dionysius of Halicarnassus came to Rome.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The period of greatest innovation in Greek literature under Rome was the "long second century" from approximately 80 AD to around 230 AD.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] This innovation was especially marked in prose, with the development of the novel and a revival of prominence for display oratory both dating to this period.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In Ancient Greek society, music was ever-present and considered a fundamental component of civilisation.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] It was an important part of public religious worship, private ceremonies such as weddings and funerals, and household entertainment.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Men sang and played music at the symposium; both men and women sang at work; and children's games involved song and dance.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek music was primarily vocal, sung either by a solo singer or a chorus, and usually accompanied by an instrument; purely instrumental music was less common.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Greeks used stringed instruments, including lyres, harps, and lutes; and wind instruments, of which the most important was the *aulos*, a reed instrument.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Percussion instruments played a relatively unimportant role supporting stringed and wind instruments, and were used in certain religious cults.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Ancient Greek mathematics contributed many important developments to mathematics, including the basic rules of geometry, the idea of formal mathematical proof, and discoveries in number theory, mathematical analysis, applied mathematics, and approached close to establishing integral calculus.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The discoveries of several Greek mathematicians, including Pythagoras, Euclid, and Archimedes, are still used in mathematical teaching today.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Greeks developed astronomy, which they treated as a branch of mathematics, to a highly sophisticated level.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The first geometrical, three-dimensional models to explain the apparent motion of the planets were developed in the 4th century BC by Eudoxus of Cnidus and Callippus of Cyzicus.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Their younger contemporary Heraclides Ponticus proposed that the Earth rotates around its axis.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos was the first to suggest a heliocentric system.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Archimedes in his treatise The Sand Reckoner revives Aristarchus' hypothesis that *"the fixed stars and the Sun remain unmoved, while the Earth revolves about the Sun on the circumference of a circle"*.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Otherwise, only fragmentary descriptions of Aristarchus' idea survive.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Eratosthenes, using the angles of shadows created at widely separated regions, estimated the circumference of the Earth with great accuracy.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the 2nd century BC Hipparchus of Nicea made a number of contributions, including the first measurement of precession and the compilation of the first star catalog in which he proposed the modern system of apparent magnitudes.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Antikythera mechanism, a device for calculating the movements of planets, dates from about 80 BC and was the first ancestor of the astronomical computer.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] It was discovered in an ancient shipwreck off the Greek island of Antikythera, between Kythera and Crete.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The device became famous for its use of a differential gear, previously believed to have been invented in the 16th century, and the miniaturization and complexity of its parts, comparable to a clock made in the 18th century.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The original mechanism is displayed in the Bronze collection of the National Archaeological Museum of Athens, accompanied by a replica.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The ancient Greeks also made important discoveries in the medical field.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Hippocrates was a physician of the Classical period, and is considered one of the most outstanding figures in the history of medicine.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] He is referred to as the "father of medicine" in recognition of his lasting contributions to the field as the founder of the Hippocratic school of medicine.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] This intellectual school revolutionized medicine in ancient Greece, establishing it as a discipline distinct from other fields that it had traditionally been associated with (notably theurgy and philosophy), thus making medicine a profession.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The art of ancient Greece has exercised an enormous influence on the culture of many countries from ancient times to the present day, particularly in the areas of sculpture and architecture.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the West, the art of the Roman Empire was largely derived from Greek models.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] In the East, Alexander the Great's conquests initiated several centuries of exchange between Greek, Central Asian and Indian cultures, resulting in Greco-Buddhist art, with ramifications as far as Japan.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Following the Renaissance in Europe, the humanist aesthetic and the high technical standards of Greek art inspired generations of European artists.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Well into the 19th century, the classical tradition derived from Greece dominated the art of the Western world.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Religion was a central part of ancient Greek life.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Though the Greeks of different cities and tribes worshipped similar gods, religious practices were not uniform and the gods were thought of differently in different places.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The Greeks were polytheistic, worshipping many gods, but as early as the 6th century BC a pantheon of twelve Olympians began to develop.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Greek religion was influenced by the practices of the Greeks' near eastern neighbours at least as early as the archaic period, and by the Hellenistic period this influence was seen in both directions.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The most important religious act in ancient Greece was animal sacrifice, most commonly of sheep and goats.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Sacrifice was accompanied by public prayer, and prayer and hymns were themselves a major part of ancient Greek religious life.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] The civilization of ancient Greece has been immensely influential on language, politics, educational systems, philosophy, science, and the arts.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] It became the *Leitkultur* of the Roman Empire to the point of marginalizing native Italic traditions.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] Via the Roman Empire, Greek culture came to be foundational to Western culture in general.
[src:alivenci/ancient-greece] A modern revival of Classical Greek learning took place in the Neoclassicism movement in 18th- and 19th-century Europe and the Americas.
[src:alivenci/arancini] A number of regional variants exist which differ in their fillings and shape.
[src:alivenci/arancini] *Arancini al ragù* produced in eastern Sicily, particularly in cities such as Catania and Messina, have a conical shape inspired by the volcano Etna.
[src:alivenci/arancini] In Sicilian, *arancini* is grammatically plural.
[src:alivenci/arancini] The corresponding singular is either the masculine *arancinu* or the feminine *arancina*.
[src:alivenci/arancini] The eastern side of Sicily tends to use the masculine form, while the western side tends to use the feminine form.
[src:alivenci/arancini] In Italian, the masculine *arancino* (pl.: *arancini*) form has become prevalent, although the feminine form *arancina* (pl.: *arancine*) can also be used.
[src:alivenci/arancini] Arancini are said to have originated in 10th-century Sicily, at a time when the island was under Arab rule.
[src:alivenci/arancini] Academic Annette Condello pinpoints arancini's origin to 18th-century southern Italy, where she says it was made to resemble oranges.
[src:alivenci/arancini] In the cities of Palermo, Syracuse, and Trapani in Sicily, arancini are a traditional food for the feast of Saint Lucy (Italian: *Santa Lucia*) on 13 December, when bread and pasta are not eaten.
[src:alivenci/arancini] This commemorates the arrival of a grain supply ship on Saint Lucy's Day in 1646, relieving a severe famine.
[src:alivenci/arancini] Today, with the increasing popularity of this finger food in Italy, arancini are found all year round at most Sicilian food outlets.
[src:alivenci/arancini] The most common type of arancini sold in Sicilian cafés is *arancini cû sucu* (transl.
[src:alivenci/arancini] *arancini al ragù*), which typically consists of meat in a tomato sauce, rice, and mozzarella or other cheese.
[src:alivenci/arancini] Many cafés also offer *arancini cû burru* (transl.
[src:alivenci/arancini] *arancini al burro*, with butter or béchamel sauce) or specialty arancini, such as *arancini chî funci* (transl.
[src:alivenci/arancini] *arancini ai funghi*, with mushrooms), *arancini câ fastuca* (transl.
[src:alivenci/arancini] *arancini al pistacchio*, with pistachios), or *arancini â norma* (transl.
[src:alivenci/arancini] In Roman cuisine, *supplì* are similar, but are commonly filled with cheese (different preparation methods and filling distribution).
[src:alivenci/arancini] In Naples, rice balls are called *pall' 'e riso*.
[src:alivenci/arancini] They are smaller than Sicilian arancini, and are not necessarily filled.
[src:alivenci/arancini] In Italian literature, Inspector Montalbano, the main character of Andrea Camilleri's detective novels, is a well-known lover of arancini—especially those made by Adelina Cirrinciò, his housekeeper and cook.
[src:alivenci/arancini] The success of the book series and the television adaptation has contributed to making this dish known outside of Italy.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] The Cantonese version of stuffed peppers is part of a street food called Three Fried Stuffed Treasures (煎釀三寶), with stuffed peppers, stuffed aubergines, and stuffed sausage.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Though with different vegetables and meat, the stuffing is all the same: dace fish paste.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] After assembling the fish paste, it is deep-fried.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] It is usually served with Worcestershire sauce, or can be served without sauce.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Stuffed peppers or **pimientos rellenos** are part of traditional Spanish cuisine, especially that of the region of the Basque Country.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] The fillings might include Manchego cheese, chicken, or cod in a red sauce, with chicken likely being the most popular recipe.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Stuffed peppers or **peperoni ripieni** are part of the Italian gastronomic tradition with its numerous regional recipes.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] The traditional Calabrian recipe, called **pipi chini**, involves the use of round bell peppers, and the filling is made with breadcrumbs, parsley, basil, Grana cheese, tomato, and provola cheese.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Sometimes hard-boiled egg, anchovies or ground meat are also added.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] In Egypt, a stuffed bell pepper dish called *mahshi felfel* (محشي فلفل) is traditionally eaten, it is a type of dolma in which bell peppers are filled with a mixture of rice and herbs.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] The filling is typically made from short-grain rice, combined with finely chopped parsley, cilantro, and dill, seasoned with cumin, coriander, salt, and black pepper.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Some versions may incorporate ground beef or lamb, but this is not typical.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Before cooking, the stuffed peppers are arranged in a pot lined with tomato slices or onion rings, preventing them from sticking.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] They are then simmered in a seasoned tomato sauce, allowing the rice to absorb the flavors while the peppers become tender.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Stuffed peppers (**bharvan mirch** or **bharva hari mirch**) is one of several stuffed vegetable (bharvan subji) dishes.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] It consists of bell peppers stuffed with cooked meat, potatoes, and onions and seasoned with chili, turmeric, coriander, cilantro, salt, and lemon juice.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] The peppers are then either browned in a *tava* (frying pan) or baked in an oven until the peppers are scorched.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Dolma is a family of stuffed dishes from the Middle East that can be served warm or cold.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Some types of dolma are made with whole vegetables including whole peppers.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Today, dolma are found in the cuisines of the Balkans, South Caucasus, Central Asia, Levant, and the family cuisines of Sephardic and Iraqi Jews.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Dolma dishes are found in Balkan, Greek, Arab, Israeli, Turkish, Central Asian, Armenian and other Caucasian cuisines.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] This dish was popular in the ancient world, although under different names, like the Ancient Greek *thrion*.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] In medieval and early modern ages, this dish was part of the Ottoman palace cuisine.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] The word dolma, of Turkish origin, means "something stuffed".
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Stuffed peppers in American cuisine is a dish where bell peppers (often the green, yellow, orange, and red varieties) are typically filled with a stuffing such as ground beef, mixed with bread crumbs or cooked rice, eggs, herbs, and spices (especially paprika and parsley) and cheese.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Recipes vary but often include hollowing out the peppers, stuffing them, covering them with cheese, and baking or alternatively cooking them on the stove top at a slow simmer in canned tomato sauce until the peppers are soft.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] A sauce may be served with them, often a tomato sauce, but this, too, varies greatly.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] In Guatemala, the "pimiento" pepper is stuffed with shredded pork and vegetables.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] As the Mexican version, it is covered with egg batter and fried.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] It is served with tomato sauce or inside a bread bun.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] The Hungarian variant, töltött paprika, is always made with Hungarian wax pepper, which has a distinctive taste somewhat similar to lecsó.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] **Punjena paprika** (pronounced [pûɲenaː pǎprika]) includes a tomato sauce.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] In Bulgaria, stuffed peppers are usually eaten with yogurt.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Another variety of stuffed peppers in Bulgaria is made with mixed white cheese and eggs instead of meat and rice as stuffing.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] In 2017, dolma making in Azerbaijan was included in the UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage Lists.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] In Romanian cuisine, stuffed peppers are usually prepared with bell peppers stuffed with ground meat (usually pork), rice, onion, and other vegetables and spices and then boiled in a sauce made from cream, tomatoes, and spices.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Traditionally in Bulgaria, the filling is made of rice steamed in advance, onions, minced meat and spices, heat-treated and crammed into pre-cleaned, washed and riddled with needle peppers.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] After filling of peppers, they are put in a baking dish, water is added and the dish is baked in the oven.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] If raw egg is added to the cooled stuffing, filled peppers can be cooked in a pan, as the pods are boiled almost steamed.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Besides minced meat and rice, other fillings may be used, such as vegetables (for example leek) and rice, beans, or fresh cheese and eggs.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] The peppers themselves can be either fresh or dried.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Dried red peppers are used especially in southeastern Serbia around Pirot and Dimitrovgrad, often in winter.
[src:alivenci/ardei-umpluți] Stuffed peppers are often cooked by Romani people and is a popular dish in Romani cuisine.
